<subsection xml:id="subsec-expressing-probability-outcomes-in-percentages-in-different-situations">
    <title>Expressing probability outcomes in percentages in different situations</title>
    <activity>
        <p>
            <m>\textbf{Work in groups}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        In a class of <m>30</m> students, each learner should mention their favorite pet from the following options: Dog, Cat, Rabbit and Parrot.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Copy and fill in the table below with the class results.
                    </p>
                    <table>
                        <title></title>
                        <tabular left="medium" right="medium" top="medium" bottom="medium"> 
                            <row halign="left" header="yes">
                                <cell>Pet</cell>
                                <cell>Tally marks</cell>
                                <cell>Number of learners(percentage)</cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell>Dog</cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell>Cat</cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell>Rabbit</cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell>Parrot</cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                            </row>
                        </tabular>
                    </table>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Convert each probability to a percentage.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Discuss and share with other groups
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </activity>
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Probability can be expressed as a percentage to show how likely an event is to occur. A probability percentage tells us the chance of an event happening out of 100.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                A probability of <m>0</m>% means the event cannot happen.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                An event with a probability of <m>50</m>% has an equal chance of occurring or not occurring.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                A probability of <m>100</m>% means the event will definitely happen.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The total probability of all possible outcomes always adds up to <m>100</m>%
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>

        </ul>
    </p>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Suppose you roll a die <m>12</m> times and the number <m>4</m> appears <m>3</m> times. Determine the probability of rolling a <m>4</m> in the next roll as a percentage.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Number of trials = <m>12</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Number of times <m>4</m> appeared = <m>3</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Using the formula:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\textbf{Probability of getting a 4} = \amp \frac{\textbf{Number of times 4 appears}}{\textbf{Total trials}}</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \frac{3}{12}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Convert to a percentage:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> = \amp \frac{3}{12} \times 100\%</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 25\%</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                You interviewed <m>10</m> classmates and asked them to name their favorite subject from the following options: Science, Maths, English, and Social Studies. The results were:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>3</m> classmates prefer Science
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>2</m> classmates prefer Maths
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>4</m> classmates prefer English
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>1</m> classmate prefers Social Studies
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            What is the probability, as a percentage, that a learner prefers English?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            What is the probability, as a percentage, that a learner prefers Science?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Number of learners who prefer English = <m>4</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Total number of learners = <m>10</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\textbf{Probability} = \amp \frac{\textbf{Number of learners who prefer English}}{\textbf{Total number of learners}}</mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \frac{4}{10}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Convert to percentage:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow> = \amp \frac{4}{10} \times 100\%</mrow>
                                <mrow> =  \amp 40\%</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            So, the probability that a learner prefers English is <m>40\%</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Number of learners who prefer Science = <m>3</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Total number of learners = <m>10</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\textbf{Probability} = \amp \frac{\textbf{Number of learners who prefer Science}}{\textbf{Total number of learners}}</mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \frac{3}{10}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Convert to percentage:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow> = \amp \frac{3}{10} \times 100\%</mrow>
                                <mrow> =  \amp 30\%</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            So, the probability that a learner prefers Science is <m>30\%</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    
</subsection>